-- PRESS DIGEST - Hong Kong - May 5
-- By Donny Kwok
-- Sun May 04, 2014 09:50PM EDT
-- None



HONG KONG, May 5 (Reuters) - These are some of the leading stories in Hong Kong newspapers on Monday. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

SOUTH CHINA MORNING POST  -- Financial Secretary John Tsang Chun-wah has urged lawmakers to agree on a compromise over the terms for electoral reform or risk damaging the city's economic future. Tsang said achieving universal suffrage by 2017 was vital to Hong Kong's political stability. (http://link.reuters.com/bup98v) -- Minority shareholders of China Resources Power Holdings <0836.HK> plan a fresh lawsuit against the firm's directors, according to sources close to the case. These shareholders had alleged the directors had breached fiduciary duties in acquisition of major coal mines in 2010. (http://link.reuters.com/cup98v) -- Brokers expect the through train stock scheme starting in October would add about 20 percent to daily market turnover and change the investing landscape by boosting the number of mainland and overseas retail investors trading in Hong Kong. (http://link.reuters.com/dup98v)  THE STANDARD -- Home transactions in Beijing during the current Golden Week plunged to a six-year low of 200 deals - a stark sign of the bearish sentiment reigning in the mainland property market. (http://link.reuters.com/jup98v) -- Hong Kong may soon see imported cases of the Middle East Respiratory Syndrome after a significant increase in the number of infections worldwide, the Hospital Authority warned. (http://link.reuters.com/hup98v) -- Secondary home transactions at major estates in Hong Kong hit a 10-month high, according to Midland Realty, with 24 units changing hands as vendors are more willing to cut prices. (http://link.reuters.com/gup98v)  HONG KONG ECONOMIC JOURNAL  -- Arrivals from mainland during the Labor Day Golden Week holiday fell for the first time in Hong Kong since 2003 when China allowed individual travel. The total number of mainland visitors during May 1-3 fell 1.6 percent to about 388,100, according to data from the Immigration Department.  HONG KONG ECONOMIC TIMES  -- Bank of China Hong Kong <2388.HK>, which issued three million credit cards in the first quarter of 2014, is studying the launch of quick response barcade payment system, according to a bank executive.